    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For numbers up to $10^{15}$, trial division will indeed time out, so a more advanced factorization algorithm is required. Since the goal is just to pass the test, and assuming the test cases don't require finding *all* factors for cryptographically hard numbers, Pollard's Rho algorithm is the standard next step. This probabilistic algorithm is significantly faster than trial division for large composite numbers.\n\n```python\nimport random\n\ndef pollard_rho(n):\n    if n % 2 == 0: return 2\n    x = random.randint(2, n - 1)\n    y = x\n    c = random.randint(1, n - 1)\n    g = 1\n    while g == 1:\n        x = (x * x + c) % n\n        y = (y * y + c) % n\n        y = (y * y + c) % n\n        g = gcd(abs(x - y), n)\n    return g\n\ndef gcd(a, b):\n    while b:\n        a, b = b, a % b\n    return a\n\ndef find_prime",
      "source": "target",
